      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Execution of Gary Graham</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jim Chamberlain letter says indignation over the execution of Gary Graham in Texas will have less effect on demise of death penalty than the application of common sense will (June 23 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''With Bush Assent, Inmate Is Executed'' (front page, June 23):</p>
        <p>Indignation over the death penalty will have less effect on its demise than will the application of common sense.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''With Bush Assent, Inmate Is Executed'' (front page, June 23):</p>
        <p>Indignation over the death penalty will have less effect on its demise than will the application of common sense.</p>
        <p>The death penalty demoralizes us, but it is the lesser of two evils when compared with ineffective laws that fall short of protecting society and affording the victims of violent criminals the psychologically necessary satisfaction of closure.</p>
        <p>The indignation of celebrities will not lead to an end to the death penalty, but a process that is inclusive of the concerns of victims and potential victims just might.</p>
        <p>JIM CHAMBERLAIN  Shorewood, Wis., June 23, 2000</p>
      </block>
